{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525930"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:18:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:18:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14102"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14102","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14102"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.27,0.46,0.08,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6772"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58927"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6772","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6772"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14102"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44337"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2196"},{"type":"tags","id":"2587"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"2900"},{"type":"tags","id":"2901"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14864"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38636"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43484"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58927"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the nephrology clinic for routine follow-up of her lupus nephritis. She was diagnosed with systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) five years ago and developed lupus nephritis two years ago. Her regular medications include hydroxychloroquine, mycophenolate mofetil, and low-dose prednisolone. She has no new symptoms and feels well.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 120/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There are no significant findings on physical examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following laboratory tests is LEAST useful for monitoring lupus nephritis activity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complement C3 level","Erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR)","Lupus anticoagulant","Proteinuria","Serum creatinine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn monitoring lupus nephritis activity, several laboratory tests are used in combination with clinical assessment to track disease progression and response to therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELupus anticoagulant\u003C/strong\u003E is an antiphospholipid antibody that, while associated with SLE, does NOT correlate with kidney inflammation or damage in lupus nephritis. Its presence or absence provides no useful information about nephritis activity, making it the least useful test for monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProteinuria\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the most sensitive markers for monitoring lupus nephritis activity. Quantitative measures such as urine protein-to-creatinine ratio directly reflect glomerular injury and respond quickly to changes in disease activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplement C3 level\u003C/strong\u003E is a valuable serological marker that typically decreases during active disease due to consumption in immune complex formation. Low complement levels often correlate with active lupus nephritis and tend to normalize with successful treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythrocyte sedimentation rate\u003C/strong\u003E, while non-specific, provides useful information about overall inflammatory activity in SLE. When interpreted alongside other markers, it contributes to the assessment of disease activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum creatinine\u003C/strong\u003E is important for monitoring kidney function in lupus nephritis, though changes may lag behind other markers. Significant elevations often indicate more severe or chronic kidney damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther useful monitoring tests include anti-dsDNA antibodies, which often correlate with disease activity. The most effective monitoring strategy combines clinical assessment with both urinary markers (especially proteinuria) and serological markers (complement levels and anti-dsDNA antibodies).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lupus anticoagulant testing is not useful for monitoring lupus nephritis activity as it does not correlate with kidney inflammation.","Proteinuria and complement levels are the most sensitive markers for monitoring lupus nephritis activity.","A comprehensive monitoring approach should include clinical assessment, urinary markers, and serological markers."],"references":["Musa R, Brent LH, Qurie A. Lupus Nephritis [Internet]. PubMed. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499817/","Moroni G, Radice A, Giammarresi G, Quaglini S, Gallelli B, Leoni A, et al. Are laboratory tests useful for monitoring the activity of lupus nephritis? A 6-year prospective study in a cohort of 228 patients with lupus nephritis. Annals of the Rheumatic Diseases. 2009;68(2):234. Available at: https://ard.bmj.com/content/68/2/234.citation-tools"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44337"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14102"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44337","links":